The '''Inland Gulf languages''' are a [[language family|family]] of [[Trans–New Guinea languages]] in the classifications of [[Stephen Wurm]] (1975) and [[Malcolm Ross (linguist)|Malcolm Ross]] (2005). The unity of the languages was established by K. Franklin in 1969. Although the family as a whole is clearly valid, Ipiko is quite distinct from the other languages.
* '''Inland Gulf''' family ** ''[[Ipiko language]]'' ** Minanibai branch: [[Minanibai language|Minanibai]] (Foia Foia), [[Mubami language|Mubami]] (Tao), [[Hoia Hoia language|Hoia Hoia]] (Hoyahoya)
[[Karami language|Karami]] was once included, but is best left unclassified for now.
Pronouns for the Minanibai branch are: :{| ! !!sg!!pl |- !1 |*no||*ni |- !2 |*go||*dau |- !3 |?||*eti |}
Ipiko only reflects 1pl *ni.
