'''Sidney T. Graves''' was a member of the [[Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors]] between 1926 and 1930. He was the only member of the county's governing body to be convicted of a crime and sent to prison. In 1933, the former supervisor was convicted of [[bribery|accepting a bribe]] concerning the building of a dam on the [[San Gabriel River (California)|San Gabriel River]]. He served three years in state prison and was released, but he had to serve more time in a federal prison for [[Tax evasion#Definition of tax evasion in the United States|evading taxes]] on the bribe.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wOkeZu6MVvwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=He+Usually+Lived+With+a+Female&hl=en&ei=DinqTIHYDY36swPs17yxCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false George Garrigues, ''He Usually Lived With a Female: The Life of a California Newspaperman,'' Los Angeles, Calif., 2006, page 106.] {{ISBN|0-9634830-1-3}}</ref>
